<article>



	<subsection xml:id="cross-product">
		<title>Cross Product</title>

		<p>
			Another important product that is defined in <m>\bbr^3</m> is the <term>Cross Product</term>
		</p>

<!-- div attr= class="definition"-->
		<p>
			Definition of Cross Product Given two vectors <m>\vec{v}</m> and <m>\vec{w}</m> in <m>3</m>-dimensional Euclidean space, write their <em>cross product</em> as <m>\vec{v}\times \vec{w}</m>. To compute it, if we have <me>\vec{v}=\begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \\  v_3\end{bmatrix}</me> and <me>\vec{w}=\begin{bmatrix} w_1 \\ w_2 \\ w_3\end{bmatrix},</me> then <me>\vec{v}\times \vec{w}=\begin{bmatrix} v_2w_3-v_3w_2 \\ v_3w_1-v_1w_3 \\ v_1w_2-v_2w_1 \end{bmatrix}.</me>
		</p><!--</div attr= class="definition">-->

		<p>
			One of the most efficient ways to compute the cross product is by way of a linear algebra algorithm known as the <term>determinant</term>. So let’s talk about determinants. The determinant of a square matrix is essentially a scalar summary of the matrix.
		</p>

<!-- div attr= class="definition"-->
		<p>
			Determinant of a <m>2\times 2</m> Matrix Let <me>M=\bmat{a&amp;b\\c&amp;d}.</me> Then the <term>determinant</term> of <m>M</m>, <m>\det(M)</m> is: <me>\det(M)=\vmat{a&amp;b\\c&amp;d}=ad-bc.</me>
		</p><!--</div attr= class="definition">-->

		<p>
			To do determinants of larger matrices, we use a technique called <em>cofactor expansion</em>.
		</p>

<!-- div attr= class="definition"-->
		<p>
			Determinant of a <m>3\times 3</m> Matrix Let <me>M=\bmat{a&amp;b&amp;c\\d&amp;e&amp;f\\g&amp;h&amp;i}.</me> Then the <term>determinant</term> of <m>M</m>, <m>\det(M)</m> is: <me>\begin{aligned}
\det(M)=&amp;\vmat{a&amp;b&amp;c\\d&amp;e&amp;f\\g&amp;h&amp;i}\\
=&amp;a\vmat{e&amp;f\\h&amp;i}-b\vmat{d&amp;f\\g&amp;i}+c\vmat{d&amp;e\\g&amp;h}\\
=&amp;a(ei-fh)-b(di-fg)+c(dh-eg).
\end{aligned}</me>
		</p><!--</div attr= class="definition">-->

<!-- div attr= class="exercise"-->
		<p>
			Determinants Find the determinant of the matrix <me>\bmat{1&amp;-1&amp;2\\-3&amp;2&amp;1\\6&amp;1&amp;-5}.</me>
		</p><!--</div attr= class="exercise">-->

		<p>
			In fact, we can use the determinant to calculate the cross product.
		</p>

<!-- div attr= class="claim"-->
		<p>
			Cross Product as a Determinant Let <me>\vcv=\bmat{v_1\\v_2\\v_3} \text{ and } \vcw=\bmat{w_1\\w_2\\w_3}.</me> Then <me>\vcv\times\vcw=\vmat{\vci &amp; \vcj &amp; \vck \\ v_1 &amp; v_2 &amp; v_3 \\ w_1 &amp; w_2 &amp; w_3}</me> where <m>\vci, \vcj, \vck</m> are the unit orthonormal vectors in 3-space, that is, <me>\vci=\bmat{1\\0\\0}, \ \vcj=\bmat{0\\1\\0}, \text{ and } \vck=\bmat{0\\0\\1}.</me>
		</p><!--</div attr= class="claim">-->

<!-- div attr= class="exercise"-->
		<p><ol>
			<li>
					<p>
			Let <m>\vcv=\bmat{3\\-1\\5}</m> and <m>\vcw=\bmat{0\\4\\2}</m>, Find <m>\vcv\times\vcw</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

			<li>
					<p>
			Let <m>\vcv=\vci+6\vcj-8\vck</m> and <m>\vcw=4\vci-2\vcj-\vck</m>. Find <m>\vcv\times\vcw</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

		</ol></p><!--</div attr= class="exercise">-->

<!-- div attr= class="definition"-->
		<p>
			Properties of the Cross Product
		</p>

		<p><ul>
			<li>
					<p>
			The cross product is anticommutative. That is, <m>\vcv\times\vcw=-\vcw\times\vcv</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

			<li>
					<p>
			The cross product is <em>not</em> associative. That is, in general, <m>\vcv\times(\vcu\times\vcw)\neq(\vcv\times\vcu)\times\vcw</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

			<li>
					<p>
			The cross product distributes over vector addition on both the left and the right. That is, <m>\vcv\times(\vcu+\vcw)=\vcv\times\vcu+\vcv\times\vcw</m> and <m>(\vcu+\vcw)\times\vcv=\vcu\times\vcv+\vcw\times\vcv</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

			<li>
					<p>
			The cross product <m>\vcv\times\vcw</m> is orthagonal to both <m>\vcv</m> and <m>\vcw</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

			<li>
					<p>
			The magnitude of the cross product <m>||\vcv\times\vcw||</m> is equal to the area of the parallelogram generated by <m>\vcv</m> and <m>\vcw</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

		</ul></p>

		<p>
			For proofs of these facts and more, refer to our Vector Operations Properties overleaf collaborative project.
		</p><!--</div attr= class="definition">-->

		<p>
			Note also that the cross product, while not defined in <m>\bbr^2</m> can still be computed over <m>\bbr^2</m> by adding an extra, zero coordinate to each vector and computing the cross product in <m>\bbr^3</m>.
		</p>

<!-- div attr= class="example"-->
		<p>
			Cross in <m>\bbr^2</m> Let <m>\vcv=\bmat{2\\-3}</m> and let <m>\vcu=\bmat{-1\\4}</m>. Let’s move these two vectors from <m>\bbr^2</m> into <m>\bbr^3</m> by padding in an extra zero in the third coordinate. So then <me>\vcv=\bmat{2\\-3\\0},\ \vcu=\bmat{-1\\4\\0}.</me> Then we can compute <m>\vcv\times\vcu</m> <me>\begin{aligned}
\vcv\times\vcu=&amp;\bmat{2\\-3\\0}\times\bmat{-1\\4\\0}\\
=&amp;\bmat{-3\cdot0-0\cdot4\\0\cdot(-1)-2\cdot0\\2\cdot4-(-3)\cdot(-1)}\\
=&amp;\bmat{0\\0\\5}.
\end{aligned}</me> Note that the resulting cross product should always orthogonal to both vectors, so certainly it should <em>always</em> be a vector that lies on the <m>z</m>-axis.
		</p><!--</div attr= class="example">-->

		<p>
			Also, just like with the dot product, the cross product has a relationship to the angle between two vectors.
		</p>

<!-- div attr= class="theorem"-->
		<p>
			Cross Products and Angles Between Vectors Let <m>\vcv</m>, <m>\vcu</m> be 2 or 3 dimensional vectors. Let <m>\theta</m> be the smallest angle between <m>\vcv</m> and <m>\vcu</m>. Then <me>||\vcv\times\vcu||=||\vcv||\cdot||\vcu||\sin(\theta).</me>
		</p><!--</div attr= class="theorem">-->

<!-- div attr= class="exercise"-->
		<p>
			Use the <term>cross</term> product to find the following angles.
		</p>

		<p><ol>
			<li>
					<p>
			Let <m>\vcv=2\vci+2\vcj</m> and let <m>\vcu=-\vci+\vcj</m>. Find the angle between <m>\vcv</m> and <m>\vcu</m>.
		</p>
			</li>

		</ol></p><!--</div attr= class="exercise">-->
